---
// SPDX-License-Identifier: Elastic-2.0
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import cockpitImg from '../assets/ui-cockpit/audit-cockpit.png';
import faultImg from '../assets/ui-cockpit/surviving-fault.png';
import verdictImg from '../assets/ui-cockpit/signed-verdict.png';
---
<section class="section" id="watch-it-back">
  <h2>Receipts, not a highlight reel</h2>
  <p>
    Every claim above is checkable against tape, not marketing copy — the
    hero you scrolled past is the exact same replay code you'd use to audit
    your own runs.
  </p>

  <div class="ui-gallery">
    <figure class="ui-fig ui-wide">
      <Image
        src={cockpitImg}
        alt="The corral cockpit replaying an audit: a canvas of agents labeled mutant-generator, test-writer, and test-critic, with a task plan on the left and a findings panel on the right."
        widths={[600, 900, 1200]}
        sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        The cockpit replaying the <code>passwd-gappy</code> audit. On the canvas,
        the decorrelated herd&nbsp;— a <strong>mutant-generator</strong>, a <strong>test-writer</strong>, and a separate <strong>test-critic</strong>&nbsp;— not a builder in sight. One scrub bar drives the whole thing.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure class="ui-fig ui-tall">
      <Image
        src={faultImg}
        alt="A task-story panel titled 'Generate seeded-violation mutants — DONE', showing the password validator source with the line 'if len(p) < 8 {' highlighted in red as the surviving planted fault, attributed to claude-writer."
        widths={[430, 640]}
        sizes="(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 430px"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        Click the mutant-generator's task and the surviving fault opens: the
        planted bug — <code>len(p) &lt; 8</code>, quietly weakening the length
        rule — highlighted against the original. The dev's tests passed anyway.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure class="ui-fig ui-wide">
      <Image
        src={verdictImg}
        alt="The cockpit console showing the audit verdict: the critic's finding in plain English, then 'the dev's tests killed 4/8 planted faults — 4 survived (the gap)', then 'NEEDS-REVIEW: kill-rate 0.5, 4 survivors, 0 proven-missed — models mutant-generator=claude-sonnet-5 test-critic=gemini-3.5-flash test-writer=claude-sonnet-5 — signed record 11'."
        widths={[600, 900, 1170]}
        sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption>
        The verdict, in plain language: the suite killed 4 of 8 planted faults,
        4 survived, and the record is <strong>signed</strong> — naming which
        model played which role. Not a green check; a receipt.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    Nothing about a finished audit is thrown away: every fault the herd
    planted, every test run against it, every kill and every survivor, each
    command an agent actually ran, and the event log itself survive
    indefinitely. A signed verdict — certified or needs-review — sits at the
    end of a record you can list, open, and re-run. Replay is read-only: it
    reconstructs the whole audit from durable rows and plays it back on the
    same corral canvas, at up to 16×. And <strong>one scrub bar moves the
    whole cockpit</strong> — canvas, plan, files, and console all snap to the
    same instant in the run, so pausing live traffic and stepping through
    history is a single control, not four.
  </p>
  <p>
    Then go deeper than the timeline: <strong>click any task</strong> — a row
    in the plan or a node on the canvas — and its whole story opens. What the
    herd was told to do, every command that ran under it, which agent (and
    which model) did it, <strong>what triggered it</strong> (the faults and
    upstream tasks it depended on), and <strong>what came next</strong> (the
    downstream work it unblocked). Every link is clickable, so you walk the
    causal chain a step at a time — the replay isn't a video, it's a queryable
    record of <em>why</em> the verdict came out the way it did.
  </p>
  <p>
    A <strong>files lens</strong> rebuilds the directory tree the herd touched,
    each path colored by the agent that claimed it, filling in as you scrub —
    the code under audit and the tests grading it appearing side by side. And
    with story capture on, each agent's own reasoning streams verbatim in the
    console, interleaved with its commands: the italic lines scrolling past are
    the model thinking out loud. Scrub back to where a fault slipped past the
    suite and watch exactly which test failed to kill it — the replay is a
    debugger for your tests, not a demo reel.
  </p>
  <p class="callout">This hero IS that player — the exact same code, replaying a real audit.</p>
  <p><a href="/recordings/">More recordings → passwd-gappy, interval-thorough, and pool-fence — three real audits, all replayable.</a></p>
</section>

<style>
  .callout { color: var(--amber); font-weight: 600; }

  .ui-gallery {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.75rem;
    max-width: 940px;
    margin: 2rem auto 2.25rem;
  }
  .ui-fig {
    margin: 0;
  }
  .ui-fig img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 10px;
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, currentColor 16%, transparent);
    box-shadow: 0 10px 30px -18px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55);
  }
  /* The fault panel is a tall modal — don't blow it up to full width. */
  .ui-tall img {
    max-width: 430px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .ui-fig figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.7rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    opacity: 0.82;
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 68ch;
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }
  .ui-fig figcaption code {
    font-size: 0.86em;
  }
</style>
